<section id="fs-id1167066015102" class="check-understanding"><title>Check Your Understanding</title><note id="fs-id1167065713623" class="os-teacher">
<title>Teacher Support</title>
<para id="fs-id1167064774265">Use these questions to assess student achievement of the section’s learning objectives. If students are struggling with a specific objective, these questions will help identify which one, and then you can direct students to the relevant content.</para>
</note>
<exercise id="fs-id1167062385114" class="os-exercise">
<problem id="fs-id1167066137414">
<!--<para id="fs-id1167065976292">
<link class="os-embed" url="#ost/api/ex/k12phys-ch16-ex009"/>
</para>-->
<para id="fs-id1169827689043">How does the object distance, d<sub>o</sub>, compare with the focal length, f, for a concave mirror that produces an image that is real and inverted?</para>
<list id="fs-id1169828355027" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha"><item>d<sub>o</sub> > f, where d<sub>o</sub> and f are object distance and focal length, respectively.</item>
<item>d<sub>o</sub> &lt; f, where d<sub>o</sub> and f are object distance and focal length, respectively.</item>
<item>d<sub>o</sub> = f, where do and f are object distance and focal length, respectively.</item>
<item>d<sub>o</sub> = 0, where do is the object distance.</item>
</list></problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id1167062957204" class="os-exercise">
